<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09156k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09156k">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09156k"> 156(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> to pollard trees</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">These negro vandals have deforested long stretches of land for the cultivation of red millet, then admit like the most advanced scientists that all this tampers with rainfall! For every fifty yards of garden about two hundred yards of adjacent <mark>trees are pollarded</mark>, branches dragged to the chosen area, heaped up to dry, then six weeks later the whole goes up in smoke to produce a rich fertilising potash. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 187</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: To pollard: to cut off the branches of a tree, leaving only the main trunk. </mm> </dd></dl>
